From Nichael Cramer Subject Re Some questions from a new Christian OFM responds to a query about reference works Aside from a commentary you might also want to consider an These are books intended for use in undergraduate Bible They give historical background discussion of literary styles And generally they have good bibligraphies for further I typically recommend Kee Froehlich and Young's NT Two other Intros to consider The Introduction by Ku mmel is a translation of a strandard NT The references are slightly dated and the style is somewhat dense but the book contains a wealth of Perrin and Duling's Intro is also very It's somewhat more modern than Ku mmel's but not quite so densely Also the authors tend to go through the books of the NT in the historical order of composition this gives a very useful perspective on the development of the There are also some good one volume Probably the best recommendation these days would be Harper's Bible A slight dissent I think the Harper's is OK but not One particular problem I have is that it tends to be pretty skimpy on bibliographic My feeling is that it is OK for quick look ups but not real useful for study in depth I keep a copy in my office at work I think there may be a couple of books with this So far as I know there is the only one book with this exact title James L Mays general editor Harper and ROw although I think I recall a older series under the name Harper Commentaries Also there's a separate Harper's Bible Dictionary most of my comments on the HC also apply to the My favorite one volume commentary is the New Jerome Biblical Commentary The NJBC is rather Catholic in focus and somewhat biased towards the The reader can decide for her or himself whether these are pluses or In any case the scholarship is by and large NOTE The NJBC is a completely reworked updated version of the Jerome Biblical Commentary copies of which can still be found on Nichael